{{Cannabis sidebar}}

'''[[Cannabis]] in [[Svalbard]]''' is illegal. Practically functioning as ungoverned [[terra nullius]] prior to the [[Svalbard Treaty]] of 1920, the [[Arctic Ocean]] archipelago dominated by [[glacier]]s and barren rock, is part of [[Norway]], and hence Norwegian law applies.<ref name="ByersBaker2013">{{cite book|last1=Byers|first1=Michael|last2=James Baker|first2=James |title=International Law and the Arctic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CUMoAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA17|date=1 August 2013|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-1-107-04275-9|pages=17–20}}</ref> Under it, there is a sliding scale approach to cannabis legislation. Possession for personal use, defined as up to 15 grams, is punished with a fine of between roughly 1,500 and 15,000 [[Norwegian krone]]r.<ref name="BBC">{{cite news |last=Brant |first=Emma |date=30 October 2014 |title=Where in the world can you legally smoke cannabis? |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/29834450/where-in-the-world-can-you-legally-smoke-cannabis |newspaper=[[BBC]] |access-date=26 October 2015 }}</ref> 
Possession of amounts larger than that is punished by jail, ranging from 6 months all the way up to 21 years.<ref name="Duthel2015">{{cite book|last=Duthel|first=Heinz |title=Illegal drug trade - The War on Drugs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7irLBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT116|date=24 February 2015|publisher=Books on Demand|isbn=978-3-7347-3432-8|page=116}}</ref> These laws are enforced by the [[Norwegian Police Service]], the small Svalbard district of which is run by the [[Governor of Svalbard]].<ref name="Sysselmannen">{{cite web |url=http://www.sysselmannen.no/en/Toppmeny/The-Governor-of-Svalbard/The-Governors-Tasks/The-Police-in-Svalbard/ |title=The police in Svalbard |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=www.sysselmannen.no |publisher=[[Governor of Svalbard]] |access-date=26 October 2015 |quote=Svalbard is an independent Norwegian police district, and the Governor is Chief of Police.}}</ref>

==Context==
With the exception of minor scientific stations, Svalbard has three main permanently inhabited settlements – the administrative capital [[Longyearbyen]], the [[Russia]]n coal mining town [[Barentsburg]], and the small research settlement [[Ny-Ålesund]]. As of 1 July 2015, the archipelago's total population is 2,677 people, in addition to large numbers of temporary workers and tourists.<ref name="Statistik">{{cite web |url=http://www.ssb.no/en/befolkning/statistikker/befsvalbard/halvaar/2015-09-24#content |title=Population of Svalbard, 1 July 2015 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=24 September 2015 |website=www.ssb.no |publisher=[[Statistics Norway]] |access-date=26 October 2015}}</ref> The use of illegal drugs is a small but growing issue within Svalbard's society, according to the [[Longyearbyen Community Council]]. While there is reportedly little evidence of an active narcotics trade in Longyearbyen, authorities are encouraged to pay close attention to the increasing liberalization of opinions relating to drug use among Svalbard's youths, and ample amounts of [[substance abuse prevention]] measures have been enacted.<ref name="Handlingsplan">{{cite book |title=Ruspolitisk handlingsplan 2012 - 2023 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=20 March 2012 |language=Norwegian |publisher=[[Longyearbyen Community Council]] }}</ref> A 2013 survey has shown that cannabis consumption among youths on Svalbard is somewhat lower than among youths on the Norwegian mainland, although certainly still existent. Significantly, only 7% of those surveyed stated that a belief that they – if they wanted to – could procure cannabis within a couple of days, compared to 41% of youths on the mainland.<ref name="Rusfag">{{cite journal |last1=Aalmen |first1=Trude |last2=Karoliussen |first2=Kent-Ronny |last3=Andreassen |first3=Marit |date=2014 |issue=1 |title=Ungdataundersøkelse viser fuktig ungdomskultur på Svalbard |url=http://borgestadklinikken.no/files/Rusfag-1-2014-artikkelsamling-komplett.pdf |journal=Rusfag |language=Norwegian |publisher=Regionale Kompetansesentre Rus |access-date=26 October 2015 }}</ref>

==2011 bust==
In 2011 the police made one of Svalbard's first drug busts, in which a total of 11 people were apprehended under suspicion of both using and selling cannabis.<ref name="ArcticJournal">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The high North |url=http://arcticjournal.com/politics/1908/high-north |newspaper=The Arctic Journal |date=21 October 2015 |access-date=26 October 2015 }}</ref> They were charged with a total of 24 offenses, which resulted in a 26 percent rise in the regional crime rate that year. One of them was later expelled from the archipelago, and another given a preliminary warning of expulsion.<ref name="Icepeople">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=25 October 2015 |title=Police arrest 11 in drug raid after lengthy investigation; some suspects may face exile from Svalbard |url=http://icepeople.net/2015/10/25/police-arrest-11-in-drug-raid-after-lengthy-investigation-some-suspects-may-face-exile-from-svalbard/ |newspaper=Icepeople |location=[[Longyearbyen]] |access-date=26 October 2015 }}</ref> That autumn, the Governor of Svalbard officially announced the presence of illegal drugs among "young adults" in Longyearbyen.<ref name="Handlingsplan"/> Following a lengthy investigation, a similar drug bust was made in October 2015, when a multi-national group of 11 men and women in their twenties were arrested and charged with, primarily, possession of cannabis, with some suspicion of [[cocaine]] usage as well.<ref name="Svalbardposten">{{cite news |last=Barstein |first=Geir |date=23 October 2015 |title=Vil vurdere utvisning etter narkoaksjon: – Enkelte av dem har saker på rullebladet fra før |language=Norwegian |url=http://svalbardposten.no/index.php?page=vis_nyhet&NyhetID=6483 |newspaper=[[Svalbardposten]] |location=[[Longyearbyen]] |access-date=26 October 2015 }}</ref> Several of those apprehended were given fines ranging between 4,000 and 9,000 Norwegian kroner.<ref name="Nordlys">{{cite news |last=Noreng |first=Susanne |date=20 October 2015 |title=11 personer tatt i politiaksjon på Svalbard |url=http://www.nordlys.no/narkotika/longyearbyen/svalbard/11-personer-tatt-i-politiaksjon-pa-svalbard/s/5-34-269999 |newspaper=[[Nordlys]] |location=[[Tromsø]] |language=Norwegian |access-date=26 October 2015 }}</ref> Whether any of them are to be expelled from Svalbard is currently under investigation. Following this event, an online poll run by the local newspaper ''[[Svalbardposten]]'' showed that 86% of respondents favored expulsion for drug crimes, although some sentiment towards legalization or decriminalization was also found.<ref name="Icepeople"/> The Governor of Svalbard,  Kjerstin Askholt, stated that her administration has zero-tolerance policy towards illegal drugs, and "will do what we can to prevent a drugs culture from establishing itself here".<ref name="ArcticJournal"/>

==Svalbard Global Seed Vault==
While cannabis is strictly illegal in Svalbard, there is one place in the archipelago that possesses an amount of it – the [[Svalbard Global Seed Vault]]. A [[seed bank]] located outside of Longyearbyen, the secure vault contains thousands of seeds from around the world, in order to ensure their preservation in case of other seed banks being destroyed or damaged during large-scale regional or global crises. Among the species of plant preserved in the vault are around 21,500 seeds belonging to the cannabis genus, donated in 2014.<ref name="NRK">{{cite news |last=Greiner |first=Robert |date=18 November 2014 |title=Her oppbevares frøene til et ulovlig rusmiddel |language=Norwegian |url=http://www.nrk.no/troms/her-oppbevares-froene-til-et-ulovlig-rusmiddel-1.12050641 |newspaper=[[NRK]] |access-date=26 October 2015 }}</ref> The seeds were provided by Alchimia, a [[Spain|Spanish]] seed bank. This will ensure the survival of cannabis, for use by future generations.<ref name="Nationen">{{cite news |last=De Rosa |first=Marie |date=15 April 2014 |title=Frøhvelvet fikk cannabis-tilbud |url=http://www.nationen.no/landbruk/frohvelvet-fikk-cannabis-tilbud/ |newspaper=[[Nationen]] |access-date=26 October 2015 }}</ref>

