{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = | name = Catherine Hollingworth | honorific_suffix = {{post-nominal|GB|OBE}}, {{post-nominal|unlinked=FRCSLT}} | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date =February 1904 | birth_place =Forfar | death_date =25 July 1999 | death_place =[[Aberdeen]] | death_cause = | occupation = {{plainlist| * Speech therapist }} | awards = | alma_mater = | thesis_year = | discipline = | sub_discipline = | workplaces = {{plainlist| *St Margaret of Scotland, Aberdeen }} }}
'''Catherine Hollingworth''',{{post-nominal|GB|OBE}}, {{post-nominal |unlinked=FRCSLT|country=GBR}} (February 1904&ndash; 25 July 1999) was a Scottish [[speech therapist]] and a pioneer of Child drama.
==Career== Hollingworth started her teaching career in speech training at [[St Margaret of Scotland, Aberdeen|St Margaret's School]] in Aberdeen in 1927 and then taught in her home town of Forfar before moving to London, where she spent time observing the work done by surgeons who were using speech therapy on their patients after throat operations. She set up her own practice as a result of these experiences. The [[Evacuations of civilians in Britain during World War II|evacuation of civilians]] during World War II prompted Hollingworth to return to Aberdeen in 1941, where she was appointed as speech specialist for the education department. The following year she founded The Children's Theatre, which went on to develop an international reputation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12276405.catherine-hollingworth/ |date=1 July 1999 |title=Catherine Hollingworth |publisher=The Herald |accessdate=27 October 2018}}</ref>
==Awards== Hollingworth was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Speech and Language Therapists]] in 1959.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rcslt.org/honours_roll_call_1945-2016 |title=RCSLT Honours Roll Call |publisher=Royal College of Speech and Language Therapists |accessdate=27 October 2018}}</ref>
She was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] in the [[1965 Birthday Honours]] whilst serving as the Superintendent of Speech Therapy and Speech Training for Aberdeen.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/43667/supplement/1 |title=Supplement to the London Gazette, 12th June 1965 |publisher=The Gazette: Official Public Record |accessdate=27 October 2018}}</ref>
Hollingworth is named in a [[commemorative plaque]] outside of the Aberdeen Municipal Children's Theatre. It reads: "CATHERINE HOLLINGWORTH 1904-1999. Child drama pioneer, speech therapist and founder of Aberdeen Municipal Children's Theatre which she directed in this building 1956-1968."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://womenofscotland.org.uk/memorials/memorial-plaque-catherine-hollingworth |title=Memorial plaque to Catherine Hollingworth |publisher=womenofscotland.org.uk |accessdate=27 October 2018}}</ref>
==Selected publications== *Hollingworth, C. 1993. ''Building bridges''. Edinburgh: Pentland Press. *Hollingworth, C. and Rennie, M. 1997. ''Another pied piper? : a personal history of my work in Aberdeen and elsewhere''. Aberdeen: Morrison & Richards.
