{{distinguish|Sand War}}

'''War sand''' is [[sand]] contaminated by remains of projectiles used in war. This kind of sand has been found in [[Normandy]], since the [[invasion of Normandy]], among other places.<ref>{{cite web|title=Microscopic Images of the Sands of Normandy Show Presence of War Sand |url= http://scitechdaily.com/microscopic-images-of-the-sands-of-normandy-show-presence-of-war-sand/|publisher=SciTech Daily|accessdate=January 5, 2013}}</ref> In 1988, the sand on [[Omaha Beach]] was discovered to contain man-made metal and glass particles deriving from [[Shrapnel shell|shrapnel]]; 4% of the sand in the sample was composed of shrapnel particles. Researchers also discovered iron and glass beads in the sand, originating from munitions explosions.<ref name=SedRec>{{cite journal|last=McBride|first=Earle F.|author2=Picard, M. Dane |title=Shrapnel in Omaha Beach sand|journal=The Sedimentary Record|date=September 2011|url=http://www.sepm.org/CM_Files/SedimentaryRecord/SedRecord%209-3.pdf|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref> 

